Differential expression analysis - single cell level

The primary function for differential expression in Seurat is FindMarkers (not FindAllMarkers). Before you run it you need to set the identifiers of the Seurat object to the metadata variable you want to use for differential expression. Here we are going to use the annotation from SingleR. Some of the key arguments for the FindMarkers function are logfc.threshold, min.pct, min.cells.feature, test.use. By default, FindMarkers uses a fold change threshold of 0.25 rather than p-value and uses the Wilcoxon test (test.use).

seu <- Seurat::SetIdent(seu, value = "SingleR_annot")
Idents(seu) <- "SingleR_annot"

# Before we run FindMarkers, let's look at the function using ?FindMarkers
# Run differential expression between T cell subtypes
deg_cd8_cd4 <- Seurat::FindMarkers(seu,
                                   ident.1 = "CD8+ T cells",
                                   ident.2 = "CD4+ T cells",
                                   group.by = seu$SingleR_annot,
                                   test.use = "wilcox")

Inspecting the output of differential expression

As mentioned above, FindMarkers uses a fold change rather than a p-value threshold so often we want to remove the genes that did not meet the adjusted p-value.

# Optionally remove the DEGs that did not meet the adjusted p-value
deg_cd8_cd4 <- subset(deg_cd8_cd4, deg_cd8_cd4$p_val_adj<0.05)
You can look for particular genes of interest as shown below.

ident.1 from FindMarkers above corresponds to pct.1 in the output while ident.2 corresponds to pct.2 in the output. A positive fold change means up in ident.1 (CD8+ T cells here) while a negative fold change means down in ident.1. Lets look at CD4 and CD8 genes to see if the results make sense.

deg_cd8_cd4[c("CD4", "CD8A", "CD8B"),]
##             p_val avg_log2FC pct.1 pct.2    p_val_adj
## CD4  2.290800e-14 -0.4085478 0.011 0.105 4.277611e-10
## CD8A 2.889582e-74  1.2738951 0.336 0.008 5.395717e-70
## CD8B 3.756143e-34  0.8521656 0.470 0.178 7.013846e-30

As you would expect (if your cell annotation is correct), CD8A and CD8B have a positive fold change showing that they are higher in CD8+ T cells. CD4 has a negative fold change meaning that it is lower in CD8 T cells than in CD8 T cells. If genes are in the opposite direction or the DEG list does not contain at least some of the genes that you would expect, you may need to redo your cell annotation.

Checking genes of interest with a plot instead of printing a table

An alternative approach is to use violin plots. Here, we are using the idents argument to only look at two of the groups from the singleR_annot column (our current active.ident) rather than plotting them all.

Seurat::VlnPlot(seu,
                features = c("CD4", "CD8A", "CD8B"),
                idents = c("CD8+ T cells", "CD4+ T cells"))

Summary

Superficially, it seems like SingleR has done a reasonable job separating between CD8 and CD4 T cells. Now lets summarise the genes using geneset enrichment analysis.

Geneset enrichment analysis

The point of geneset enrichment analysis is to summarise your list of differentially expressed genes, as often you will have hundreds or sometimes thousands. Geneset enrichment uses databases of known gene functions and groups/pathways with popular ones including gene ontology (GO), Reactome, KEGG, and MSigDb. The statistical basis of enrichment analysis is asking if there are more genes from these known gene groups/pathways than what we would expect. For example, if we chose 100 genes at random, how many genes would we expect there to be from the immune response Gene Ontology term.

# install packages if necessary
# BiocManager::install(c("org.Hs.eg.db","clusterProfiler","enrichplot"))
library(org.Hs.eg.db)
library(clusterProfiler)
library(enrichplot)

Run enrichment analysis using clusterProfiler

As always, look at the arguments of the function before you use it with ?enrichGO. Keytype specifies whether you are using gene symbol, ensembl ID, entrezgene etc, minGSSize sets the minimum size of the GO results - GO terms start from very broad terms (eg biological process) and get progressively smaller and more specific. You can also alter maxGSSize (default value is 500) to remove the large vague ones. These default maximum and minimum values vary considerably depending on the enrichment method that you are using. If you are running more than one then keep the parameters the same.

# Set up annotation
AnnotationDbi::keytypes(org.Hs.eg.db)

Removing Gene ontology redundancy

Gene ontologies have a tree-based structure, so results can often include multiple very similar terms. This is referred to as redundancy. clusterProfiler has a function called simplify that removes terms based on a user-defined threshold (cutoff argument).

# Try and remove some of the redundancy in the results
enr_go <- clusterProfiler::simplify(cd8_vs_cd4_go,cutoff=0.7)

# Make a graph using emap plot - connections on the plot reflect
# the similarity between the terms. change showCategory to show more/less terms
enrichplot::emapplot(enrichplot::pairwise_termsim(enr_go),
                     showCategory = 10)

Note on geneset enrichment analysis

There are web-based platforms that you can use for enrichment analysis as well. These can be helpful if you have found a gene list from somewhere such as a publication. I have previously used WebGestalt and StringDB (links below). https://www.webgestalt.org/ and https://string-db.org/ (go to search on StringDB and then select multiple proteins, paste your gene list into the box). The two websites have different default settings for minimum/maximum gene set sizes and are updated at different times so results will tend to be similar but not identical.

Save outputs

No need to save our Seurat object as we havent added anything to it this time. You can save your differential expression and enrichment results. It can be a good idea to save them both as a csv and RData file if you are planning on opening the results in Excel.

# Save csv files
write.csv(deg_cd8_cd4,file="deg_cd8_cd4_findmarkers.csv")
write.csv(cd8_vs_cd4_df,file="deg_cd8_cd4_enrichGO.csv")

# Save RData files
save(deg_cd8_cd4,file="deg_cd8_cd4_findmarkers.RData")
save(cd8_vs_cd4_df,file="deg_cd8_cd4_enrichGO.RData")

Pseudobulk analysis

In a pseudobulk analysis the counts for each gene are aggregated across cells to get a single count value per sample for each gene (the same format as if you were doing a bulk RNA-seq experiment). Typically aggregation is done across cells belonging to a particular cell type, and seperate differential expression analyses are run for each cell type. Pseudobulk analysis can produce more reliable results but does require that you have replicates for each group. We have only been using three control samples until now. For this exercise we will use a separate Seurat object with three controls and three tumour samples.

Load and explore the new Seurat object

# Load the Seurat object
proB <- readRDS("course_data/proB.rds")

Pseudobulk preparation

Firstly, we make sure that we are using the RNA assay and then I am going to make a new column in the metadata called sample (not essential but I prefer sample to orig.ident).

# Set default assay
Seurat::DefaultAssay(proB) <- "RNA"
# Make sample column
proB$sample <- factor(proB$orig.ident)
# set our identifier as sample
Seurat::Idents(proB) <- proB$sample

Aggregate the counts across cells for each sample

Here we are using the AggregateExpression function to make pseudobulk counts. Note that we are using the raw counts (counts slot) because the differential expression methods expect unnormalised counts. Here, we will get Aggregate expression to return a Seurat object so that we can get our metadata easily as well.

proB_summed_seurat <- AggregateExpression(proB,group.by = "sample",assays = "RNA",
                                          slot = "counts",return.seurat = T)
## Centering and scaling data matrix
# Extract the counts
summed <- GetAssayData(proB_summed_seurat,assay = "RNA",slot = "counts")
# Convert the counts into a dataframe rather than a sparse matrix
summed <- as.data.frame(as.matrix(summed))

Set up the covariates file

# Extract the metadata as a dataframe from the Seurat object
summed_meta <- proB_summed_seurat[[]]

Differential expression using DESeq2

This is a very superficial example of the main steps using DESeq2. There are further visualisation/quality steps that are worth doing as well. I would highly recommend going through the DESeq2 vignette on the Bioconductor website - http://bioconductor.org/packages/devel/bioc/vignettes/DESeq2/inst/doc/DESeq2.html

library(DESeq2)

# make a DESeq object with our counts and metadata as input. Design is the comparison
# that we are doing (the group variable in this case).
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(summed,
                              colData = summed_meta,
                              design = ~ group)
## converting counts to integer mode
## Warning in DESeqDataSet(se, design = design, ignoreRank): some variables in
## design formula are characters, converting to factors
# By default, DESeq2 runs on all genes. You can optionally filter out genes that have
# very low expression. Here we remove genes that don't have a total count of at least 10.
keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds <- dds[keep,]

# Run differential expression
dds <- DESeq(dds)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
# See the names of the comparisons in the DESeq2 object
resultsNames(dds) # lists the coefficients

Notes on comparison

There is substantial overlap between FindMarkers and DESeq2 but there are also several hundred genes that only come up in a single method. Another thing worth noting is the incredibly small p-values in the FindMarkers results compared to DESeq2. This demonstrates the p-value inflation observed when running differential expression at the single cell level compared to pseudobulk.

Enrichment analysis using MSigDB

Firstly, you need to define your MSigDB list of interest. Here we are using the human Hallmark geneset (category H = Hallmark). For further information about the available genesets refer to https://www.gsea-msigdb.org/gsea/msigdb

gmt <- msigdbr::msigdbr(species = "human", category = "H")

# You also need to specify the "universe" which is all of the non-significant genes

cd8_vs_cd4_msigdb <- clusterProfiler::enricher(gene = rownames(deg_cd8_cd4),

Pseudobulk analysis using limma

Feel free to use this example or follow along with the more complex example on the SIB website - https://sib-swiss.github.io/single-cell-training/day3/day3-1_differential_gene_expression.html. You need to filter out lowly expressed genes before running limma. There is a function called filterByExpr that does this automatically but it is on the stringent side. Alternatively you can keep genes that have total counts over a certain value or are above a certain value across a certain number of cells. The main thing is to remove genes that are mostly zeroes across all samples and there is a fine balance between removing noise and preserving biological signal. Filter too harshly, and you can lose lowly expressed (but still potentially informative) genes. Filter too leniently, and the noise from extremely lowly expressed genes can make your differential expression model less accurate.

#BiocManager::install(c("limma","edgeR"))
library(limma)
## 
## Attaching package: 'limma'
## The following object is masked from 'package:DESeq2':
## 
##     plotMA
## The following object is masked from 'package:BiocGenerics':
## 
##     plotMA
library(edgeR)

# You can filter out genes that don't have at least 10 counts in total
reads_fil <- summed[which(!rowSums(summed)<=10),]
dim(reads_fil)
## [1] 13650     6
# Or filter out the genes that don't have at least a certain number of counts
# in a certain number of samples (at least 5 counts in 3 samples here)
reads_fil <- summed[rowSums(summed >= 5) >= 3, ]
dim(reads_fil)
## [1] 11533     6

The filterByExpr method

#keep <- filterByExpr(y, group=summed$group)
#y <- y[keep,]
##see how many genes were kept
#summary(keep)

Set up object and run differential expression

# As in the standard limma analysis generate a DGE object
y <- DGEList(reads_fil)

# create design matrix
## Create the design matrix and include the technology as a covariate:
design <- model.matrix(~0 + group,data = summed_meta)

# Have a look
head(design)
##              groupETV6_RUNX1 groupPBMMC
## ETV6-RUNX1-1               1          0
## ETV6-RUNX1-2               1          0
## ETV6-RUNX1-3               1          0
## PBMMC-1                    0          1
## PBMMC-2                    0          1
## PBMMC-3                    0          1
# specify the comparison that you wnat to do
contrast.mat <- limma::makeContrasts(groupETV6_RUNX1 - groupPBMMC,
                                     levels = design)

# normalise for gene length
dge <- edgeR::calcNormFactors(y)

#variance stabilising transformation using voom
vm <- limma::voom(dge, design = design, plot = TRUE)

# fit the limma model and run differential expression
fit <- limma::lmFit(vm, design = design)
fit.contrasts <- limma::contrasts.fit(fit, contrast.mat)
fit.contrasts <- limma::eBayes(fit.contrasts)
